nt changes** – If a deployment to payments‑service or checkout‑service occurred shortly before the incident, roll it back. <br>4. **Increase timeout** – As an interim patch, raise the timeout for the payment request (e.g., from 800 ms to 3 s) to see if the service recovers while root‑cause work proceeds. |\n| **Next steps / investigation** | - **Metrics:** Check latency & error‑rate metrics for the payments service and network latency between checkout and payments. <br>- **Owner paging:** Alert the *payments‑service* and *checkout‑service* owners (e.g., `@team-payments`, `@team-checkout`). <br>- **Log deep‑dive:** Pull full logs around the incident window (including upstream service logs) to confirm whether the timeout is due to downstream dependency slowness or internal processing. <br>- **Health‑checks:** Verify that the payments service health endpoint reflects the OPEN circuit‑breaker state and investigate why the breaker tripped (e.g., insufficient failures threshold). <br>- **Post‑mortem prep:** Record the timeline, root‑cause hypothesis, and mitigation actions for a formal post‑mortem. |\n\n---\n\n### Draft Post‑mortem Skeleton\n\n1. **","sequence":0,"stepIndex":4,"turnId":"turn_0"},"type":"message.appended","meta":{"at":"2026-06-18T15:42:17.431Z"}}
